# AGENTS.md вЂ” how this agent is built

This file describes how this agent is structured: the file layout, the
MVC split, the build chain, and the high-level UI conventions. It is the
authoritative reference for *this* repo's shape.

> **Airlock-managed вЂ” do not edit.** Airlock regenerates this file from
> its scaffold template on every build (build housekeeping), so any edits
> here are overwritten. Put agent-specific decisions in `NOTES.md`, which
> Airlock never touches.

Two other documents complete the picture:

- **`/libs/agentsdk/llms.md`** вЂ” the agentsdk API reference. Every
  `Register*` function, the LLM-calling APIs, storage, seal/unseal,
  built-in JS bindings, the full surface. Read it for "what does the
  SDK give me?" вЂ” read this file for "how do I wire it together?".
- **`NOTES.md`** вЂ” the agent-specific design log. Decisions made for
  *this* agent (chosen integrations, non-obvious trade-offs, the
  styling palette, anything a future upgrade needs to know about).
  Keep it short and current as you go.

## What "an app" usually means

Requests are often a single line вЂ” "build me a Spotify app", "a kanban
board", or just "I want an app". Unless the user clearly asks for something
narrower (one chat tool, a webhook, a cron), read "app" as **a web app plus
the tools that drive it**, not one or the other:

- A **web UI** вЂ” templ + htmx pages (see the HTML UI section) the user opens
  in a browser to see and manipulate their data.
- **LLM-callable tools** (`RegisterTool`) over the *same* domain, so the agent
  can do the same things conversationally (Telegram / Discord / web chat).
- The **state, connections, and schedules** that domain needs behind both.

The UI and the tools are two faces of one domain layer (`service.go`) вЂ” build
both against it. A bare tool with no UI, or a UI the agent can't operate over
chat, is usually half of what the user pictured. When the request is vague,
pick a concrete domain, build the full web-app-plus-tools shape, and record the
assumption in `NOTES.md`.

## Workspace structure

```
{agent-repo}/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ main.go            # Entrypoint вЂ” registrations only
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ handlers/          # CONTROLLERS вЂ” HTTP handlers; import domain + views
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ home.go
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ views/             # VIEW вЂ” templ templates + view-model types
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ layout.templ
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ index.templ
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ viewmodel.go   # HomeView (and any other view-model types)
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ assets.go      # //go:embed compiled Tailwind + AppCSSPath
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ static/        # Tailwind build output (gitignored)
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ styles/
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ app.css        # Tailwind v4 + DaisyUI source
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ deps/
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ deps.go        # Deps struct вЂ” shared by all domain packages
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ db/
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ migrations/    # goose migrations (you create; doc.go pre-scaffolded)
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ queries/       # sqlc query files (you create)
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ internal/db/       # sqlc-generated code
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ Dockerfile         # Generated вЂ” do not edit
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ setup.sh           # (optional) system setup вЂ” runs as root at image build
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ go.mod
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ sqlc.yaml
в””в”Ђв”Ђ NOTES.md           # Agent-specific design log
```

**Keep `main.go` thin.** Registrations only вЂ” `RegisterTool`,
`RegisterRoute`, `RegisterWebhook`, `RegisterCron`, `RegisterConnection`,
etc. Business logic lives in domain packages, never inline in main.

## MVC: handlers are the integration point

The scaffold uses an MVC split for the HTML UI. As the agent grows, you'll
add domain packages and HTTP handlers; the rule below keeps the package
graph cycle-free.

```
main.go      в†’   <domain> (model)
                 handlers (controller) в†’ <domain> + views
                 views (view)
```

- **Model** вЂ” domain packages (`spotify/`, `kanban/`, `weather/`). Pure
  Go: types, business logic, API calls. Never imports `views/` or
  `handlers/`.
- **View** вЂ” `views/` holds templ templates plus view-model types
  (`views.HomeView`, `views.BoardView`). Templates take view-model
  types only; `views/` never imports a domain package.
- **Controller** вЂ” `handlers/` holds HTTP handlers (`handlers.Home`,
  `handlers.BoardPage`). Handlers import both domain packages and
  `views/`, do the modelв†’view-model conversion, and render. Nothing
  imports `handlers/` back.

**If you find yourself wanting to import `views` from a domain
package, the handler is in the wrong place вЂ” move it to `handlers/`.**
That single rule prevents the cycle that would otherwise form:
domain в†’ views в†’ domain.

## Domain package shape

`Deps` is shared across every domain package, so it lives in `deps/` вЂ”
not inside any feature package. A feature package can't be imported by a
sibling without coupling them, and `main` can't be imported at all.

Each domain package has two layers:

1. **Pure Go** вЂ” business logic, API calls. Accepts handles, returns
   plain types.
2. **Tool Execute** вЂ” `func(ctx, In) (Out, error)` that pulls handles
   via `agentsdk.GetDeps[*deps.Deps](ctx)` and calls into the pure
   layer. These are what `RegisterTool` exposes to the LLM.

A typical domain package:

```
spotify/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ service.go  # NewService(...) + methods returning plain types
в””в”Ђв”Ђ tools.go    # SearchTracks, PlayTrack, etc. вЂ” RegisterTool targets
```

LLM-callable tools live in `tools.go`. HTTP routes live in `handlers/`.
Both consume the pure layer in `service.go`; neither imports the other.

## Build chain

Every time you change a `.templ`, edit `styles/app.css`, or modify any
Go source, run the chain end-to-end before declaring the build done:

```bash
go mod tidy
go tool templ generate
tailwindcss -i styles/app.css -o views/static/app.css --minify
go build -buildvcs=false -o /tmp/agent .
```

`go mod tidy` runs FIRST. Airlock bumps `agentsdk`'s required version in
`go.mod` before each build (so the build resolves against the current
SDK), but it doesn't touch `go.sum` вЂ” so the chain has to reconcile the
sums before `go tool templ generate` can resolve the templ tool
dependency. Putting tidy first turns the trial-and-error you'd
otherwise hit ("missing go.sum entryвЂ¦") into a single clean pass.

Run `sqlc generate` whenever `db/queries/*.sql` changes вЂ” only then,
since regenerating without a query change is noise.

Not committed (the Docker build regenerates them inside the image):
- `*_templ.go` вЂ” regenerated from `.templ`
- `views/static/app.css` вЂ” regenerated by tailwindcss

Committed:
- `internal/db/` (sqlc output) вЂ” the Docker build does **not** run sqlc, so
  the generated code must be in the tree for a fresh-clone `docker build .` to
  compile. Update it on demand whenever a query changes.

So a fresh clone + `docker build .` works: templ/tailwind are regenerated, and
the committed sqlc output + your source are already present.

## Database

Migrations under `db/migrations/`, schema-modifying SQL only. Use
goose's naming convention (`NNN_short_description.sql`) and
sequential numbering. Query files under `db/queries/` are sqlc input;
each `-- name: FuncName :one|:many|:exec` block becomes a typed Go
function in `internal/db/`.

To validate migrations locally when `$TEST_DB_URL` is set:

```bash
goose -dir db/migrations postgres "$TEST_DB_URL" up
goose -dir db/migrations postgres "$TEST_DB_URL" reset
goose -dir db/migrations postgres "$TEST_DB_URL" up
psql "$TEST_DB_URL" -c "\dt"  # verify final schema shape
```

## Dockerfile & system setup

**Never modify `Dockerfile`** вЂ” Airlock regenerates it. System packages,
language runtimes, and binary tools the agent needs at runtime go in
`setup.sh`, which runs as root at image build time and is baked into
the runtime image. Example:

```bash
# setup.sh
apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends ffmpeg
# Drop tool binaries under /var/agent/bin/ вЂ” already on PATH at runtime.
```

After editing `setup.sh`, verify it works inside the toolserver with:

```bash
sudo run-setup && <new-binary> --version
```

## HTML UI вЂ” short

Stack: `templ` (type-safe HTML) + `htmx` (interactivity) + Tailwind v4 +
DaisyUI (styling). htmx is served same-origin by the framework under
`agentsdk.Assets.HTMX`; the compiled Tailwind stylesheet is served from
the agent's own `/static/app.{hash}.css` route (see `views/assets.go`
and `main.go`'s `/static/{name}` handler).

Design principles:

- **Pick a tone before writing markup.** Music dashboard, weather
  agent, admin console вЂ” each earns a distinct aesthetic. Decide
  first; build to it. A centered title + three buttons is the stock-
  demo trap.
- **Mobile-first.** Design for narrow viewports, then add `sm:` /
  `md:` / `lg:` variants for wider screens. Test at ~375px before
  declaring done.
- **Brand through DaisyUI's theme**, not per-element overrides.
  Configure the theme block in `styles/app.css`. Don't sprinkle
  `bg-[#...]` or inline `style=` colours through templates.
- **Show the domain.** Render real data prominently вЂ” album art,
  weather illustrations, charts. Emoji-as-title-decoration is a
  placeholder you replaced.
- **Don't double-wrap htmx swap targets.** Either the page owns the
  card and the partial swaps inner content, or the partial owns the
  card and the page renders only an empty target. Picking both
  produces two stacked headers and a card-in-a-card border.
- **Record styling decisions in `NOTES.md`** вЂ” chosen theme name (or
  custom palette tokens), font family + where it's loaded from,
  layout conventions you committed to. The next rebuild should see
  what you decided.

## Keeping the UI live

Agents mutate state from *two* directions: the user editing in the web
UI, and the LLM running tools over chat (Telegram, Discord, web chat).
A board the user is looking at can grow new cards mid-session because
they told the bot "add a card for X" in another tab. The web view must
reflect that without a manual reload.

The pattern: render every data-bearing region as its own template, then
poll it from the page with htmx. The page is a shell; the partials
refresh themselves.

```go
// views/board.templ
templ Board(v BoardView) {
    @BoardCards(v) // initial render so the page isn't empty pre-poll
}

templ BoardCards(v BoardView) {
    <div id="board-cards"
         hx-get="/board/cards"
         hx-trigger="load, every 5s [document.visibilityState === 'visible']"
         hx-swap="outerHTML"
         class="grid вЂ¦">
        for _, c := range v.Cards { @Card(c) }
    </div>
}
```

Rules:

- **One handler per refreshable region.** `GET /board/cards` returns
  the partial template only вЂ” no layout, no surrounding chrome. Same
  view-model shape as the embedded initial render so they stay in
  sync.
- **`[document.visibilityState === 'visible']`** on every polling
  trigger. Without it, htmx keeps polling for a hidden tab вЂ” quiet
  battery drain on phones and useless load on the agent.
- **Match the cadence to the data.** Kanban / queue / chat-log feel:
  3вЂ“5s. Slower-moving lists (members, settings): 15вЂ“30s. Anything that
  shouldn't auto-change: don't poll, refresh on user action.
- **Don't double-wrap.** The polled element IS the swap target вЂ” its
  outer `<div id="board-cards">` must match the partial's. Wrapping
  again on the page produces nested duplicates (see the rule above
  about htmx swap targets).
- **User actions still drive optimistic updates** вЂ” POSTs from the UI
  should swap their own response immediately rather than waiting for
  the next poll. Polling is the *fallback* that catches chat-side
  mutations.
